kind of started at
19 as-- You know,

00:34:27.750 --> 00:34:32.440
you started working
with that author.

00:34:32.440 --> 00:34:34.639
But I'd like to kind of
take it a little bit.

00:34:34.639 --> 00:34:37.850
The thing that strikes me most,
and I'm sure a lot of people

00:34:37.850 --> 00:34:42.320
here, you give off a sense of
like this relentless, sharp,

00:34:42.320 --> 00:34:45.769
focus that all these
kids that supposedly, you

00:34:45.769 --> 00:34:47.949
know, still live with
their parents at 35

00:34:47.949 --> 00:34:49.409
probably don't display.

00:34:49.409 --> 00:34:52.120
And I would like you to talk
a little bit about-- I mean,

00:34:52.120 --> 00:34:55.439
it's like all of the rest of
the stuff stems from that.

00:34:55.439 --> 00:34:56.230
RYAN HOLIDAY: Sure.

00:34:56.230 --> 00:34:57.771
AUDIENCE: You've
got this huge drive,

00:34:57.771 --> 00:35:00.046
and then you figured
out how to-- If you

00:35:00.046 --> 00:35:01.300
could talk about that.

00:35:01.300 --> 00:35:02.841
RYAN HOLIDAY: No,
that's interesting.

00:35:02.841 --> 00:35:07.190
I've always been sort of a very
intense person I would say.

00:35:07.190 --> 00:35:08.980
I think there's
sort of an intensity

00:35:08.980 --> 00:35:11.340
mixed with sort of
introvertedness, which

00:35:11.340 --> 00:35:14.310
works well for what I
do, because it forces

00:35:14.310 --> 00:35:18.039
you to sort of go internal,
and sort of nagging things

00:35:18.039 --> 00:35:19.580
that you're just
focused on until you

00:35:19.580 --> 00:35:21.010
can get them to make sense.

00:35:21.010 --> 00:35:23.470
So I guess it's always
been that way for me,

00:35:23.470 --> 00:35:27.200
but I sort of start
with 19 because up

00:35:27.200 --> 00:35:31.400
until that point I guess I
was just a normal college

00:35:31.400 --> 00:35:37.310
student that got a
series of lucky breaks

00:35:37.310 --> 00:35:39.600
that introduced me to
people that taught me a lot.

00:35:42.142 --> 00:35:42.850
But I don't know.

00:35:42.850 --> 00:35:44.600
Like my childhood was
pretty unremarkable.

00:35:47.950 --> 00:35:49.990
It wasn't like Steve
Jobs growing up next

00:35:49.990 --> 00:35:53.140
to like the dude who created
Hewlett Packard, or whatever.

00:35:53.140 --> 00:35:54.790
There was no thing like that.

00:35:54.790 --> 00:35:58.140
It was just in college
I met some people

00:35:58.140 --> 00:36:00.690
and started down this
path, and I've always

00:36:00.690 --> 00:36:01.840
been very intense about it.

00:36:01.840 --> 00:36:03.881
AUDIENCE: But there's
nothing during high school,

00:36:03.881 --> 00:36:07.940
or during earlier schooling
that shows a difference in focus

00:36:07.940 --> 00:36:08.440
between--

00:36:08.440 --> 00:36:09.898
RYAN HOLIDAY: No,
I don't think so.

00:36:09.898 --> 00:36:12.700
I mean, I've thought a lot about
it, but there's nothing there.

00:36:15.260 --> 00:36:15.990
I wish there was.

00:36:15.990 --> 00:36:19.390
It would make it
easier to explain this.

00:36:19.390 --> 00:36:22.730
AUDIENCE: I guess I have maybe
two questions, but one I think

00:36:22.730 --> 00:36:24.440
is quick.

00:36:24.440 --> 00:36:27.750
Growing up you said you'd
had a lifelong obsession

00:36:27.750 --> 00:36:28.570
with reading.

00:36:28.570 --> 00:36:33.160
Was there like any kind
of shift in genre or book

00:36:33.160 --> 00:36:34.020
that drew you in?

00:36:34.020 --> 00:36:37.380
Or did you always love
biographies, or historical,

00:36:37.380 --> 00:36:40.070
or fiction, or escapist
fantasy, or whatever?

00:36:40.070 --> 00:36:42.320
RYAN HOLIDAY: I think what
my parents did pretty early

00:36:42.320 --> 00:36:45.995
on is they gave me like all--
My dad was a police officer

00:36:45.995 --> 00:36:49.560
and my mom was like
a school principal.

00:36:49.560 --> 00:36:52.390
They were just
very like educated,

00:36:52.390 --> 00:36:53.810
but like civil servant types.

00:36:53.810 --> 00:36:56.746
So they gave me
their favorite books,

00:36:56.746 --> 00:36:58.620
which just happened to
be the books that they

00:36:58.620 --> 00:37:00.240
read in high school and college.

00:37:00.240 --> 00:37:02.076
But they gave them
to me pretty early.

00:37:02.076 --> 00:37:03.450
So it was like,
by the time I got

00:37:03.450 --> 00:37:04.380
to like middle school
and high school

00:37:04.380 --> 00:37:05.755
I'd already read
all those books.

00:37:05.755 --> 00:37:07.730
So it was like, what
comes after that?

00:37:07.730 --> 00:37:15.040
So I think I'm just a testament
to the compounding returns

00:37:15.040 --> 00:37:17.370
that come from having
an early start.

00:37:17.370 --> 00:37:19.685
That's the only-- I mean,
I thought a lot about it,

00:37:19.685 --> 00:37:21.382
and there was no
like, oh, you know,

00:37:21.382 --> 00:37:23.590
I got introduced to this
book and it changed my life,

00:37:23.590 --> 00:37:26.540
or I saw this person talk
and it changed everything.

00:37:26.540 --> 00:37:27.790
There wasn't really like that.

00:37:27.790 --> 00:37:31.380
It was just, you know, I'm just
reading "Lord of the Flies"

00:37:31.380 --> 00:37:33.340
in fourth grade, or fifth
grade, or something,

00:37:33.340 --> 00:37:34.756
when I should have
been reading it

00:37:34.756 --> 00:37:36.600
in freshman year of high school.

00:37:36.600 --> 00:37:40.450
And so that allowed me to start
asking questions and seeing

00:37:40.450 --> 00:37:43.580
things maybe a little bit early.

00:37:43.580 --> 00:37:45.210
AUDIENCE: And then
the second question

00:37:45.210 --> 00:37:50.620
is, is there a particular
book or work that you really

00:37:50.620 --> 00:37:51.939
wish that you had done?

00:37:51.939 --> 00:37:53.980
RYAN HOLIDAY: Is there a
book I wish I'd written?

00:37:53.980 --> 00:37:54.605
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:37:54.605 --> 00:37:57.160
If you read something and
said, wow, I wish that was me.

00:37:57.160 --> 00:38:00.230
RYAN HOLIDAY: I'm a
big Nicholas Taleb fan.

00:38:00.230 --> 00:38:02.250
So I think "The Black
Swan" is pretty amazing.

00:38:05.330 --> 00:38:08.140
One of the people in the
book is Samuel Zamurray,

00:38:08.140 --> 00:38:11.060
who was the founder
of United Fruit.

00:38:11.060 --> 00:38:12.530
He's not a good person.

00:38:12.530 --> 00:38:15.950
But there was a really
interesting biography

00:38:15.950 --> 00:38:19.520
of him called "The Fish
That Ate the Whale"

00:38:19.520 --> 00:38:22.990
that I liked a lot that I
probably wish that I'd written.

00:38:22.990 --> 00:38:26.740
I think most of the books
that I thought were amazing

00:38:26.740 --> 00:38:30.830
that I wish I'd written were
probably like biographies,

00:38:30.830 --> 00:38:33.440
because I just can't wrap my
head around writing like a 900

00:38:33.440 --> 00:38:36.700
page book about someone,
and not only writing it,

00:38:36.700 --> 00:38:39.840
but having no factual
errors, and being

00:38:39.840 --> 00:38:43.770
able to sort of live inside
this person and produce this--

00:38:43.770 --> 00:38:44.430
I don't know.

00:38:44.430 --> 00:38:49.870
Just the mammoth size of that
task is very impressive to me.

00:38:54.710 --> 00:38:57.510
AUDIENCE: So you
mentioned really at 19

00:38:57.510 --> 00:39:00.410
you were interested, slash
excited about blogging.

00:39:00.410 --> 00:39:02.560
And, you know, you sort
of was charting a bit

00:39:02.560 --> 00:39:05.070
about sort of the arc
of that, maybe how

00:39:05.070 --> 00:39:08.080
it's maybe going down at this
point in time, the lack of RSS

00:39:08.080 --> 00:39:10.120
feeds and what have
you, and maybe it's

00:39:10.120 --> 00:39:11.660
turning into sort
of advertising.

00:39:11.660 --> 00:39:14.310
I'm curious, because
you've connected

00:39:14.310 --> 00:39:18.180
in a great way blogging to how
that's produced sort of more

00:39:18.180 --> 00:39:20.811
publishing opportunities, is
there a new technology today,

00:39:20.811 --> 00:39:22.560
or is there a technology
front that you're

00:39:22.560 --> 00:39:25.000
excited about that
kind of connects,

00:39:25.000 --> 00:39:27.910
if not in the same way, but
has that sort of same feeling

00:39:27.910 --> 00:39:29.480
for you that blogging once did?

00:39:32.110 --> 00:39:34.330
RYAN HOLIDAY: I don't know.

00:39:34.330 --> 00:39:37.739
Obviously I think books are
really exciting right now.

00:39:37.739 --> 00:39:39.280
I think you're seeing
a lot of people

00:39:39.280 --> 00:39:40.720
do cool things in like audio.

00:39:40.720 --> 00:39:43.510
I think you're seeing
cool stuff in audio right

00:39:43.510 --> 00:39:47.430
now, both like on podcasting
and in audiobooks.

00:39:47.430 --> 00:39:49.180
It's never sort of
been cheaper and easier

00:39:49.180 --> 00:39:51.800
to produce like
professional quality stuff.

00:39:51.800 --> 00:39:57.820
And then with
smartphones and broadband

00:39:57.820 --> 00:40:00.730
you can store this stuff really
easily or access it easily.

00:40:00.730 --> 00:40:04.280
So I think audio books used
to be the thing that you could

00:40:04.280 --> 00:40:08.300
only listen to in your car,
and you had to have nine CDs

00:40:08.300 --> 00:40:09.050
or whatever.

00:40:09.050 --> 00:40:11.940
And now it's like it's just one
thing in iTunes or whatever.

00:40:11.940 --> 00:40:12.870
Right?

00:40:12.870 --> 00:40:14.560
So I think that's interesting.

00:40:14.560 --> 00:40:18.449
But there's no one technology
that's like, oh, I love this,

00:40:18.449 --> 00:40:20.240
I think this is going
to change everything.

00:40:20.240 --> 00:40:22.520
And that might just
be because having

00:40:22.520 --> 00:40:24.910
seen that happen with
blogging I'm a little jaded,

00:40:24.910 --> 00:40:28.970
and I think that sort of--
That one of my favorite writers

00:40:28.970 --> 00:40:34.850
is Evgeny Morozov,
where his sort of point

00:40:34.850 --> 00:40:37.430
is that technology
just allows us

00:40:37.430 --> 00:40:39.850
to be more or less
who we actually are.

00:40:39.850 --> 00:40:44.354
And so I've lost some of
that idealism about like,

00:40:44.354 --> 00:40:46.520
oh, this is going to make
everything so much better.

00:40:46.520 --> 00:40:48.990
It's like, no, you're going
to see the same people doing

00:40:48.990 --> 00:40:50.830
the same things,
just like you're

00:40:50.830 --> 00:40:53.539
seeing some of the same
Hollywood economics now

00:40:53.539 --> 00:40:56.080
be applied to the people who
are creating content on YouTube,

00:40:56.080 --> 00:40:56.900
or whatever.

00:40:56.900 --> 00:40:59.190
It's all, at the end of
the day, it's the same.

00:41:04.687 --> 00:41:05.603
AUDIENCE: Hello Senor.

00:41:05.603 --> 00:41:06.350
RYAN HOLIDAY: Yes.

00:41:06.350 --> 00:41:07.391
AUDIENCE: Quick question.

00:41:07.391 --> 00:41:10.036
What's on your iPod right now?

00:41:10.036 --> 00:41:12.410
RYAN HOLIDAY: I would prefer
not to answer that question,

00:41:12.410 --> 00:41:15.900
because I listen
to terrible music.

00:41:15.900 --> 00:41:18.680
My thing is that I listen
to the same songs like over,

00:41:18.680 --> 00:41:20.200
and over, and over again.

00:41:20.200 --> 00:41:22.810
And then I throw
them away after,

00:41:22.810 --> 00:41:24.775
because I'm so
sick of them, and I

00:41:24.775 --> 00:41:28.010
feel so disgusted that I would
have listened to this song

00:41:28.010 --> 00:41:29.439
300 or 400 times.

00:41:29.439 --> 00:41:30.980
AUDIENCE: But it
helps though, right?

00:41:30.980 --> 00:41:32.230
RYAN HOLIDAY: Yeah, of course.

00:41:32.230 --> 00:41:35.550
And I think it's like very
good for like focusing.

00:41:35.550 --> 00:41:37.570
The music becomes
background noise.

00:41:37.570 --> 00:41:39.920
The music replaces
the background noise,

00:41:39.920 --> 00:41:42.829
and then all that's left is
like whatever you're working on.

00:41:45.424 --> 00:41:47.340
AUDIENCE: I'll get your
recommendations later.

00:41:47.340 --> 00:41:49.172
RYAN HOLIDAY: Yeah.

00:41:49.172 --> 00:41:52.780
I don't think you're
going to like them.

00:41:52.780 --> 00:41:53.780
AUDIENCE: Two questions.

00:41:53.780 --> 00:41:55.350
One is when do you read?

00:41:55.350 --> 00:41:57.670
Do you ritualize you're
reading, like in the morning,

00:41:57.670 --> 00:41:59.045
or a certain time,
or do you just

00:41:59.045 --> 00:42:00.780
read whenever you
feel like reading?

00:42:00.780 --> 00:42:02.696
RYAN HOLIDAY: I'm more
of like a binge reader.

00:42:02.696 --> 00:42:05.742
So if I'm travelling I'll
read like a ton of books,

00:42:05.742 --> 00:42:08.200
and then if I'm home and I'm
busy I might not read anything

00:42:08.200 --> 00:42:08.949
for a couple days.

00:42:08.949 --> 00:42:12.840
So it's me it's more I read
whenever I have a chance,

00:42:12.840 --> 00:42:14.990
and I try to increase
that by always

00:42:14.990 --> 00:42:16.600
like carrying a
book around with me.

00:42:16.600 --> 00:42:19.710
So it's like, you know, let's
say I have to be here at 10:30.

00:42:19.710 --> 00:42:21.530
Maybe I'm going to
get here at 10:15,

00:42:21.530 --> 00:42:24.154
and like read
for-- You know, I'm

00:42:24.154 --> 00:42:26.730
going to try to squeeze
reading in like little blocks

00:42:26.730 --> 00:42:27.516
like that.

00:42:27.516 --> 00:42:31.180
AUDIENCE: What motivates
you to put the effort

00:42:31.180 --> 00:42:33.989
to do all this-- Like
what drives that?

00:42:33.989 --> 00:42:34.780
RYAN HOLIDAY: Yeah.

00:42:34.780 --> 00:42:37.182
And I call it a
note card system.

00:42:37.182 --> 00:42:39.390
If you Google like my name,
and that, you can see it,

00:42:39.390 --> 00:42:41.473
and I have pictures, and
I've sketched it all out.

00:42:41.473 --> 00:42:42.540
But like this is my job.

00:42:42.540 --> 00:42:46.350
I mean, I'm supposed
to find-- Like when

00:42:46.350 --> 00:42:50.030
I write books I need to have
examples, and stories, and data

00:42:50.030 --> 00:42:51.260
to make my argument.

00:42:51.260 --> 00:42:53.980
So it's somewhat
unfair in that I

00:42:53.980 --> 00:42:55.840
get paid to produce this system.

00:42:55.840 --> 00:42:59.900
So it's not like I'm doing it
for fun because I'm very OCD.

00:42:59.900 --> 00:43:04.160
It's like this is what I have
to do to produce what I produce.

00:43:04.160 --> 00:43:07.154
But even if I didn't I
would still probably do it--

00:43:07.154 --> 00:43:08.570
And I had a version
of this system

00:43:08.570 --> 00:43:14.907
before I learned it-- Because
I think it's important.

00:43:14.907 --> 00:43:16.490
I mean, one of the
big sections that I

00:43:16.490 --> 00:43:20.910
have is just like life advice,
just weird, interesting

00:43:20.910 --> 00:43:23.400
perspectives that I might not
have thought of otherwise,

00:43:23.400 --> 00:43:26.170
that I might want to
go back to at some time

00:43:26.170 --> 00:43:27.670
if I'm like dealing
with something

00:43:27.670 --> 00:43:28.878
or struggling with something.

00:43:34.530 --> 00:43:35.760
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:43:35.760 --> 00:43:38.970
Is there anything else
that you can attribute

00:43:38.970 --> 00:43:42.130
to your success besides
reading, and social networking,

00:43:42.130 --> 00:43:43.850
and obviously your drive?

00:43:43.850 --> 00:43:46.860
Like is there anything?

00:43:46.860 --> 00:43:48.590
RYAN HOLIDAY: Well,
one would be luck.

00:43:48.590 --> 00:43:49.089
Right?

00:43:49.089 --> 00:43:52.657
I think that's a
lot of people don't.

00:43:52.657 --> 00:43:54.240
It's like, hey, I
emailed this person.

00:43:54.240 --> 00:43:56.712
He got back to me, and then
another good thing happened,

00:43:56.712 --> 00:43:58.670
and another good thing
happened, and it sort of

00:43:58.670 --> 00:43:59.310
builds from there.

00:43:59.310 --> 00:44:01.120
So I think that's
obviously very important.

00:44:01.120 --> 00:44:03.078
But that probably doesn't
answer your question.

00:44:03.078 --> 00:44:14.210
So I've hired and fired
my fair share of people.

00:44:14.210 --> 00:44:18.670
And like I hire people.

00:44:18.670 --> 00:44:20.160
I'm very excited about them.

00:44:20.160 --> 00:44:23.330
And then so often they
end up not working out,

00:44:23.330 --> 00:44:24.920
because two things.

00:44:24.920 --> 00:44:26.260
They don't want it, right?

00:44:26.260 --> 00:44:28.920
And I seem to want them to be
more successful than they want

00:44:28.920 --> 00:44:31.100
to be for themselves, and
that's very frustrating.

00:44:31.100 --> 00:44:34.240
Or two, like they're
just nuts, like

00:44:34.240 --> 00:44:36.725
they just have so many,
especially young people,

00:44:36.725 --> 00:44:38.890
like they have so many issues.

00:44:38.890 --> 00:44:41.430
And it's like, look, I'm
hiring you to do this job,

00:44:41.430 --> 00:44:44.170
not because I want to be like
involved in your personal life,

00:44:44.170 --> 00:44:45.850
or I want to hear
why you couldn't

00:44:45.850 --> 00:44:47.420
do this because of that.

00:44:47.420 --> 00:44:51.770
So for me it was like I
wanted this stuff really bad,

00:44:51.770 --> 00:44:54.910
and I wasn't going to
let any things that I

00:44:54.910 --> 00:44:56.960
was dealing with
interfere with that.

00:44:56.960 --> 00:44:59.540
So it was like sort
of not all business,

00:44:59.540 --> 00:45:01.950
but like when it was
business it was all business.

00:45:01.950 --> 00:45:05.470
And so I think taking
care of yourself

00:45:05.470 --> 00:45:08.740
and being well
adjusted, and centered,

00:45:08.740 --> 00:45:11.310
and healthy is very important.

00:45:11.310 --> 00:45:14.469
And it's sort of part
of the job as well.

00:45:14.469 --> 00:45:16.510
AUDIENCE: Can you talk a
little bit more-- Sorry,

00:45:16.510 --> 00:45:17.370
it's another question.

00:45:17.370 --> 00:45:17.560
RYAN HOLIDAY: Yeah.

00:45:17.560 --> 00:45:19.226
AUDIENCE: Can you
talk a little bit more

00:45:19.226 --> 00:45:21.569
about how you became Director
for the American Apparel?

00:45:21.569 --> 00:45:22.360
RYAN HOLIDAY: Yeah.

00:45:22.360 --> 00:45:24.909
So this probably doesn't
apply for any other company

00:45:24.909 --> 00:45:26.950
because American Apparel
is a little bit unusual,

00:45:26.950 --> 00:45:29.520
but when I came in American
Apparel had no marketing

00:45:29.520 --> 00:45:31.620
department.

00:45:31.620 --> 00:45:34.840
And the company was probably
a $400 million a year

00:45:34.840 --> 00:45:38.040
company at this point
with 10,000 employees.

00:45:38.040 --> 00:45:40.870
But there was like
a guy over here

00:45:40.870 --> 00:45:43.090
who kind of did some
marketing stuff, and then

00:45:43.090 --> 00:45:45.718
someone over here who sent out,
you know, product placement,

00:45:45.718 --> 00:45:47.426
and then there was
someone else over here

00:45:47.426 --> 00:45:48.970
who was designing ads.

00:45:48.970 --> 00:45:52.937
And part of what Dov
brought me in to do

00:45:52.937 --> 00:45:54.270
was sort of organize that stuff.

00:45:54.270 --> 00:45:56.700
So I ended up building
the marketing department.

00:45:56.700 --> 00:46:01.350
Like literally our office was at
one point like a large storage

00:46:01.350 --> 00:46:05.750
closet for broken sewing
machines at the factory.

00:46:05.750 --> 00:46:09.080
And so we cleared that out,
and that became the office.

00:46:09.080 --> 00:46:11.540
So I ended up becoming
the Director of Marketing

00:46:11.540 --> 00:46:14.000
because it was like
I built it, and there

00:46:14.000 --> 00:46:15.930
wasn't anyone else
to be in charge.

00:46:15.930 --> 00:46:22.740
And so it was this sort of
totally random accumulation

00:46:22.740 --> 00:46:28.110
of stuff that led to
me being the director.

00:46:28.110 --> 00:46:30.670
And American Apparel is like a
vertically integrated company.

00:46:30.670 --> 00:46:34.720
So like Dov, the owner and CEO,
is like my only direct boss.

00:46:34.720 --> 00:46:37.430
So it probably
couldn't have worked

00:46:37.430 --> 00:46:43.650
at Urban Outfitters or somewhere
else, but it's been very cool.

00:46:43.650 --> 00:46:45.120
I got to learn so
much on the job.

00:46:48.940 --> 00:46:52.030
What I like about marketing
is you do this thing,

00:46:52.030 --> 00:46:54.149
and then you can
like see in real time

00:46:54.149 --> 00:46:56.065
whether it's like driving
people to the store,

00:46:56.065 --> 00:46:59.360
or it's driving sales, or
you put out this thing,

00:46:59.360 --> 00:47:01.152
and then a reporter's
calling you

00:47:01.152 --> 00:47:02.443
and they want to talk about it.

00:47:02.443 --> 00:47:04.470
So marketing has been
very cool for me,

00:47:04.470 --> 00:47:06.180
and my role at
American Apparel was

00:47:06.180 --> 00:47:09.240
about creating some
semblance of strategy

00:47:09.240 --> 00:47:11.370
behind that, because
it wasn't there before.

00:47:11.370 --> 00:47:12.971
It was just very scattered.

00:47:12.971 --> 00:47:14.720
AUDIENCE: Sorry, will
be my last question.

00:47:14.720 --> 00:47:15.678
RYAN HOLIDAY: Whatever.

00:47:15.678 --> 00:47:17.734
AUDIENCE: So in
terms of marketing,

00:47:17.734 --> 00:47:20.150
would you say that you just
attended a lot of conferences,

00:47:20.150 --> 00:47:23.320
and how you got into that in
terms of social networking?

00:47:23.320 --> 00:47:26.560
RYAN HOLIDAY: I've definitely
been to a lot of conferences.

00:47:26.560 --> 00:47:31.020
I could probably count on one
hand with like half my fingers

00:47:31.020 --> 00:47:34.940
how many of those conferences
I really got something out of.

00:47:34.940 --> 00:47:38.034
I think a lot of people
focus on those things

00:47:38.034 --> 00:47:39.950
because it's like what
everyone else is doing.

00:47:42.510 --> 00:47:44.760
The conferences that I've
gotten the most of that I've

00:47:44.760 --> 00:47:47.800
met the most people
at-- I was actually

00:47:47.800 --> 00:47:51.720
at a Google conference in
London like two weeks ago

00:47:51.720 --> 00:47:52.780
called Google Create.

00:47:52.780 --> 00:47:55.184
It was very cool that I
met all these people at.

00:47:55.184 --> 00:47:56.600
It was one of the
best conferences

00:47:56.600 --> 00:47:57.700
I've probably ever been to.

00:47:57.700 --> 00:47:59.950
But it was like totally
random, and most of the people

00:47:59.950 --> 00:48:01.810
were not talking
about marketing.

00:48:01.810 --> 00:48:04.670
So I tend to find that
it's going to the things

00:48:04.670 --> 00:48:07.390
that you don't know
that much about.

00:48:07.390 --> 00:48:09.020
Like you go to
South by Southwest,

00:48:09.020 --> 00:48:12.200
it's like there's 250,000
other people there

00:48:12.200 --> 00:48:13.844
attending this conference.

00:48:13.844 --> 00:48:15.760
You're not going to get
face time with people.

00:48:15.760 --> 00:48:17.635
You're probably not
going to learn that much.

00:48:17.635 --> 00:48:20.130
Everyone is there just
as an excuse to party.

00:48:20.130 --> 00:48:22.490
Is that the place that you're
going to get the most out

00:48:22.490 --> 00:48:23.090
of it?

00:48:23.090 --> 00:48:25.510
And is that worth a week
of your life, or whatever?

00:48:25.510 --> 00:48:30.570
So one, I try to think
about attending the ones

00:48:30.570 --> 00:48:32.070
that other people
aren't attending.

00:48:32.070 --> 00:48:34.670
And then I've also found that
if you're speaking at-- So

00:48:34.670 --> 00:48:37.480
I would much rather
speak at a conference

00:48:37.480 --> 00:48:42.800
than attend a conference, even
if that conference I'm speaking

00:48:42.800 --> 00:48:47.220
at is much less prestigious
and much smaller than the one

00:48:47.220 --> 00:48:50.022
that I'm attending, because it
sort of changes the dynamic,

00:48:50.022 --> 00:48:52.230
and you have a different
relationship with the people

00:48:52.230 --> 00:48:53.520
that you're meeting.

00:48:53.520 --> 00:48:58.309
I went to this one like
sort of private-- I

00:48:58.309 --> 00:48:59.850
guess this is a good
example-- I went

00:48:59.850 --> 00:49:02.075
to this private
conference, and Keith-- I

00:49:02.075 --> 00:49:03.950
don't know if you know
who Keith Ferrazzi is,

00:49:03.950 --> 00:49:06.440
but he wrote that book
"Never Eat Alone."

00:49:06.440 --> 00:49:07.320
And he spoke.

00:49:07.320 --> 00:49:09.940
And I was talking to the
host, and he was like, yeah,

00:49:09.940 --> 00:49:15.174
I invited Keith, and he was
like, hey, do you want to come?

00:49:15.174 --> 00:49:16.340
It's this thing at my house.

00:49:16.340 --> 00:49:18.880
And he was like, I'll
come only if I can speak.

00:49:18.880 --> 00:49:19.890
And I was like, what?

00:49:19.890 --> 00:49:21.850
And he's like, he only
goes to conferences

00:49:21.850 --> 00:49:25.200
he can speak at, because
of that exact thing.

00:49:25.200 --> 00:49:29.672
It just changes the dynamic
of how you meet people,

00:49:29.672 --> 00:49:31.630
and how they perceive
you, and stuff like that.

00:49:31.630 --> 00:49:32.730
So that might be
like a little trick.

00:49:32.730 --> 00:49:33.563
